#: ../../configuration.md:608
msgid "Backups"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:610
msgid ""
"In your projects, the daemon is a central element and it's where the data"
" are stored. In reality, the data you manipulate (identities, messages, "
"...) is only a tiny part of the data that the daemon manage. It's this "
"invisible data that needs to be saved, as it enables secure exchange with"
" the bot's contacts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:614
msgid "Warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:617
msgid ""
"Please carefully review the following recommendations and warnings before"
" continuing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:619
msgid ""
"Backups contain sensitive data equivalent to the daemon's data directory."
" It is imperative to handle them with the same rigor and level of "
"security."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:620
msgid ""
"Backups mentioned here are Olvid backups, which do not contain messages "
"or attachments. These backups allow you to restore your contact book and "
"groups, but not the discussion content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:621
msgid ""
"Backups are ... backups. You will have to save them in a safe place to be"
" able to re-use them if necessary. In a production environment, the "
"minimal best practice would be to store backups on a separate disk from "
"the rest of the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:622
msgid ""
"Restoring a backup on another daemon and running both simultaneously will"
" lead to unpredictable behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:625
msgid "Setup automatic backups"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:627
msgid ""
"Daemon automatically and periodically creates backup. Backups are created"
" every time it's necessary (your  bot added a contact, joined or left a "
"group, ...). These backups are stored in `/daemon/backups` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:630
msgid ""
"If you want to persist these backups you need to mount the "
"`/daemon/backups` directory as a volume. Here is an example in a `docker-"
"compose.yaml` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:641
msgid "Here is an example of `/daemon/backups` directory tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:651
msgid ""
"Each subdirectory (0001, 0002) must contains it's own `backup_seed.txt` "
"file daemon will increment and create a new directory. This backup seed "
"is necessary to decrypt and restore backups, without the seed your backup"
" is unusable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:654
msgid ""
"Inside a subdirectory the daemon create and stores up to 10 backup files "
"before rotating them. All these backups are named with their creation "
"epoch timestamp."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:656
msgid "Restore a backup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:659
msgid ""
"Restoring a backup is not a trivial action and should only be done as a "
"last resort. You will lose all your stored messages and attachments in "
"the daemon during this process. Only elements saved using the storage API"
" will still be available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:664
msgid ""
"To restore a backup you will need a fresh daemon installation. If you "
"want to reset an existing daemon delete the `data` folder content (this "
"data is probably mounted as a volume on host system)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:667
msgid ""
"Daemon will also need to access backup files, so we will need another "
"volume."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:680
msgid ""
"Then choose the backup to restore in your backups (it's most of the time "
"the most recent). Save the subdirectory and backup file name for later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:682
msgid ""
"Now we will need to start daemon in a recovery mode and tell him to "
"restore our backup. There are two solutions, we can use `docker compose` "
"or `docker run`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md
msgid ":octicon:`command-palette;1em` docker compose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:689
msgid ""
"With docker compose you can reuse your current docker-compose.yaml file "
"by verifying beforehand that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:691
msgid "The data volume has been properly cleared."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:692
msgid "Backup directory has been mounted to /daemon/backups."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:693
msgid ""
"All other running services have been stopped using the command docker-"
"compose down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:695
msgid ""
"Then you can start backup restoration with the following command. Do not "
"forget to replace the backup subdirectory (0001) and filename "
"(backup-1569233400.bytes) with your own values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md
msgid ":octicon:`command-palette;1em` docker run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:707
msgid ""
"First check that your original daemon is not running and the data "
"directory you will mount is empty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:709
msgid ""
"Here is an example of ``docker run`` command to adapt to your situation. "
"Mind to check the volume location on host system, daemon image version, "
"your backup subdirectory and file name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:720
msgid ""
"When you see the message `💾 BackupRestoration: Finished backup "
"restoration process`, you can stop the daemon (CTRL + C) and start it "
"normally with the command `docker-compose up -d`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../configuration.md:722
msgid ""
"You can now verify using the CLI that the restoration was successful. You"
" should find your identities, contacts, groups, client keys, ..."
msgstr ""

